{"parse":{"title":"Altarpiece of the Halberd","pageid":31723138,"revid":851210700,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox vevent\" style=\"width:22em;width: 22em; line-height: 1.4em; text-align: left; float:right;\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" class=\"summary\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold;font-size: 125%; font-weight: bold; font-style: italic\">Altarpiece of the Halberd</th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:Lotto,_pala_dell%27Alabarda_01.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Lotto, pala dell&#39;Alabarda 01.jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/27/Lotto%2C_pala_dell%27Alabarda_01.jpg/300px-Lotto%2C_pala_dell%27Alabarda_01.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"410\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/27/Lotto%2C_pala_dell%27Alabarda_01.jpg/450px-Lotto%2C_pala_dell%27Alabarda_01.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/27/Lotto%2C_pala_dell%27Alabarda_01.jpg/600px-Lotto%2C_pala_dell%27Alabarda_01.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1901\" data-file-height=\"2597\" /></a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Artist</th><td class=\"attendee\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/Lorenzo_Lotto\" title=\"Lorenzo Lotto\">Lorenzo Lotto</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Year</th><td>\nc. 1539</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Medium</th><td class=\"category\">\nOil on canvas</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Dimensions</th><td>\n294&#160;cm&#32;\u00d7&#160;216&#160;cm&#32;(116&#160;in&#32;\u00d7&#160;85&#160;in)</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right:0.65em;\">Location</th><td>\nPinacoteca civica Francesco Podesti, Ancona</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p>The <b>Altarpiece of the Halberd</b> is a painting from around 1539  by the <a href=\"/wiki/Italy\" title=\"Italy\">Italian</a> <a href=\"/wiki/High_Renaissance\" title=\"High Renaissance\">High Renaissance</a> painter <a href=\"/wiki/Lorenzo_Lotto\" title=\"Lorenzo Lotto\">Lorenzo Lotto</a>. It is housed in the <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Pinacoteca_civica_Francesco_Podesti&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Pinacoteca civica Francesco Podesti (page does not exist)\">Pinacoteca civica Francesco Podesti</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/Ancona\" title=\"Ancona\">Ancona</a>, central Italy.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Altarpiece_of_the_Halberd&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The work was seen by the art biographer <a href=\"/wiki/Giorgio_Vasari\" title=\"Giorgio Vasari\">Giorgio Vasari</a> in the church of <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Sant%27Agostino,_Ancona&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Sant&#39;Agostino, Ancona (page does not exist)\">Sant'Agostino</a> in Ancona, where Lotto had fled in reply to the hostility received in Venice. It was later moved to the church of <a href=\"/wiki/Santa_Maria_della_Piazza\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Santa Maria della Piazza\">Santa Maria della Piazza</a> and, after other locations, the current one. \n</p><p>The painting dates to a few years after the <a href=\"/wiki/Coup\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Coup\">coup</a> by which Ancona had been restored to the <a href=\"/wiki/Papal_States\" title=\"Papal States\">Papal States</a>. The resistance had been brutally suppressed, many of the rebels having been beheaded by order of the papal legate. The upside-down <a href=\"/wiki/Halberd\" title=\"Halberd\">halberd</a> has been thus interpreted as a symbol of peace.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Description\">Description</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Altarpiece_of_the_Halberd&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Description\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The monumental composition is taken directly from the tradition of <a href=\"/wiki/Holy_Conversation\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Holy Conversation\">Holy Conversations</a> in the <a href=\"/wiki/Venetian_school_(art)\" title=\"Venetian school (art)\">Venetian School</a>, inaugurated by <a href=\"/wiki/Antonello_da_Messina\" title=\"Antonello da Messina\">Antonello da Messina</a>'s <a href=\"/wiki/San_Cassiano_Altarpiece\" title=\"San Cassiano Altarpiece\">San Cassiano Altarpiece</a>. It shows the Madonna and Child on a high throne, with two angels holding the crown (a 15th-century <a href=\"/wiki/Flemish_painting\" title=\"Flemish painting\">Flemish painting</a> element also in use in Italy). In the lower part are four saints: Stephen, John the Evangelist, <a href=\"/wiki/Simon_the_Zealot\" title=\"Simon the Zealot\">Simon the Zealot</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/St._Lawrence\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"St. Lawrence\">Lawrence</a>. Simon is holding the <a href=\"/wiki/Halberd\" title=\"Halberd\">halberd</a> which gives its name to the altarpiece. At the sides of the throne, between columns and draperies, are two sections of sky with clouds. \n</p><p>Like in other Lotto's works, the symmetry is broken by the variety of postures and gestures; the work is general characterized by a certain archaic style, explainable by the relatively provincial commissioners and the late stage of his career.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Sources\">Sources</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Altarpiece_of_the_Halberd&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Sources\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><cite class=\"citation book\">Pirovano, Carlo (2002). <i>Lotto</i>. Milan: Electa.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Lotto&amp;rft.place=Milan&amp;rft.pub=Electa&amp;rft.date=2002&amp;rft.aulast=Pirovano&amp;rft.aufirst=Carlo&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAltarpiece+of+the+Halberd\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li></ul>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2256\nCached time: 20180914061610\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.144 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.190 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 675/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 5716/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 492/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 14/40\nExpensive parser function count: 1/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 0/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.071/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 3.15 MB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%  171.785      1 -total\n 77.22%  132.651      1 Template:Infobox_Artwork\n 58.97%  101.302      1 Template:Infobox\n 22.70%   39.002      1 Template:Cite_book\n 22.44%   38.543      2 Template:Convert\n  6.67%   11.458      2 Template:Comma_separated_entries\n  5.82%   10.001      1 Template:Italic_title\n  2.61%    4.486      7 Template:Isnumeric\n  2.59%    4.446      1 Template:If_empty\n  1.46%    2.515      1 Template:Template_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:31723138-0!canonical and timestamp 20180914061610 and revision id 851210700\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[{"lang":"es","url":"https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Retablo_de_la_Alabarda","langname":"Spanish","autonym":"espa\u00f1ol","*":"Retablo de la Alabarda"},{"lang":"it","url":"https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pala_dell%27Alabarda","langname":"Italian","autonym":"italiano","*":